Introduction¶

Fake news is a broad term and in this project specifically in this notebook, we will dive into fake and real articles. We will see what the data we have, how it was collected then we will have a basic understanding of the data. Next, we will explore the data by asking questions and coming up with hypotheses about the data. In addition to that, we shall analze a sample of data to see what potentional problems in the data. Last, we will display our findings in a short way to conclude the notebook.

Problem understanding¶

News can be in many different forms. For example, Newspapers, Magazines, TV and radio, Internet, News agencies and Alternative media. Now, there are some businesses that try to promote their products or to advertise a product and some publish fake, attractive or charming news as 'clickbait' and we tend to be curious when it comes to unusual things and so we read / check the content. For instance, in 1835 newspaper company claimed that they have found out creates live in moon (humans with wings) here is link for full article. That as a consequence allowed the company to be more popular which allowed them to promote and advertise more. Now this is one of the reasons why would certain group of people / a person publish fake news or misleading information. However, the influnce on the reader is usually harmful. For example, it could be that fake news regards healthy food suggest or recommend some types of food for people who suffer from kind of illness and if reader followed the suggestions that could be in fact harmful for them since news were fake in the first place. There are more scenarios obviously but this is where the problem lies. Fake news in general are published for the sake of obtaining profit most of the time and readers might believe misleading information which could influence their decisions.

In this research though, the focus will be on the news of covid-19 topic (tweets) and various topics of fake, legit articles published on the internet.

Research question¶

  • Based on the classified online articles as fake and real 'How is it possible to predict whether a new article tends to be fake or real?'

With this question in mind, the part of predicting the reliability of online articles should be clear (half of the project) and the other half (fake and legit fake tweets) will be in another notebook.

Data requirement¶

In this section I will describe the obtained data, its format, the number of columns and rows in addition to a description of each column.

Description of obtained data¶

The dataset is about online articles which was taken from fake articles kaggle dataset and real articles from All Sides during 2015 and 2016. The dataset I am currently using is the one after it has been merged, check out the Data Gather/Wrangling part

Format of the data¶

The acquired dataset of online articles is in CSV-format which can be easily stored locally on the machine.

General information about the dataset¶

The acquired dataset of covid-19 tweets consists of 6335 rows and 4 columns.

The columns being as the following:

  • Unnamed: 0, which represents a unique number for each article in the dataset.

  • title, which represents the title of the online article.

  • text, which represent the context or the body of the online article.

  • label, which represents whether an article was considered to be fake or real.

Where the data can be obtained?¶

How the data can be obtained?¶

  1. Cloning the repository:
  • This way you will be able to clone a copy of the entire repository via git command line. (first you will have to dowbload git).
  • Open a folder you desire to have the cloned repository in.
  • Copy the repository link.
  • Open the git commander and type 'git clone (repository link)' and hit enter.

Potential problems can be encountered?¶

  • The second approach of obtaining the repository can be a bit difficult to people who never worked with git before, therefore they can receive errors in command line due to some type errors or incorrect git setup. It is a powerful version control system but can be tricky for beginners.

Remarks¶

  • After downloading the repository the dataset is in .csv.zip file extension which needs to be renamed to .csv in order to work with the data.

  • The data contains the label column which was assigned by kaggle fake online articles and real articles taken from allsides. The merged dataset in its final form was provided in this research.

  • The data contains the 'Unnamed: 0' column which represent a unique identifier and that can be dropped since we would not use it probably.

Findings¶

After counting the number of characters, words and sentences for each article I tried to find out what was the relationship between the length and the reliability. I found out that in the dataset there are outliers in terms of length and if you zoom in to where outliers are not in your scope range you will notice that the more length of sentenecs, characters and words the more it leans towards being real article. On average articles that have 50 sentences, 1000 words orabout 5000 characters tend to be real.

hypothesis: I think that if the article has more length, it should be leaning towards truth because more length means more information being displayed and more clarification to the subject.

Therefore, the hypothesis was correct the data shows that the more length of an article the higher chance of it being real.

The following function takes in the data and title to spit out word cloud data visualization

In [14]:
# Function for generating word clouds
def generate_wordcloud(data,title):
  wc = WordCloud(width=400, height=330, max_words=150,colormap="Dark2").generate_from_frequencies(data)
  plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
  plt.imshow(wc, interpolation='bilinear')
  plt.axis("off")
  plt.title('\n'.join(wrap(title,60)),fontsize=13)
  plt.show()

I will create now a matrix where each row represent a word that was present in the corpus of each fake and real with the corresponding reliability. Also stop words such as 'The, I, you' are words that occur too often but does not actually influence what we are trying to do therefore I will remove them in the CountVectorizer parameter.

Findings¶

  • We can notice that words such as election, president, hillary and government appear often in fake articles.

  • We notice that there are no http or www mentioned in both fake and real articles which indicates that rarely articles provide hypper links.

  • We can notice that words such as voters, democratic, political and law appear often in real articles.

  • We can notice that there are some words that appear in both fake and real articles. For example, Trump, Said, clinton appear in both kind of articles but the emphasis is different.

  • We notice that the majority of articles in the dataset about election / politics / law.

Things to be noticed¶

  • Text can be all lowered case.
  • Text contain punctuations for example, article 1 has dots.
  • Text contain stopwords. For example, article 5 contains words such as We and This.
  • Text contain emoji. For example, article 5 contains this emoji ☢
  • text contain short contraction. For example, 4 mentioned this 'It’s a joint effort from patriots hailing from every corner of the world.' It's is a short contractioned and the expanded version is It is
  • Text contain digits. for example, article 2 mentioned 9,800 troops

Note: Keep in mind that the model that is going to be created should give results according to keywords of the articles, thus digits should not matter. Distinguishing 'fake' or 'real' articles based on keywords is possible but not with digits included (atleast in my project).

Findings¶

After analyzing a sample of the data we have derived that the text contain some problems such as capalization, punctuations, short contractions (example, It's), a few emojis in the text and the text contain digits which would not be useful for us in the prediction section.

Therefore the list of fixes for the text as follows:

  1. Lowercase all the text
  2. Expand Contractions
  3. Remove punctuations
  4. Remove emojis
  5. Remove digits

After that we should have clean text, but in order to continue processing it we would need to remove stopwords as they appear often in text corpus while not indicating actual meaning and need to use lemmatization technique in order to bring the words from various tense forms into their base form (example. 'Went' --use lemma--> 'Go')

Conclusions¶

To conclude this notebook, although fake news is a broad term our focus in this research was on online articles and covid-19 tweets (which is covered in different notebook.), fake news in general are published for the sake of obtaining profit most of the time and readers might believe misleading information which could influence their decisions.

The data we worked on contains 4 columns Unnamed 0,title,text and label around 6335 rows while Unnamed 0 indicate a unique identifier, title indicates the title of the article,text indicate body of the article and the label indicate the reliability of the article. The current dataset is a merged balanced data provided as open-source for purposes of classifying fake and real articles. The dataset can be easily stored in machine locally due to its size and its format. There are some duplicated titles and body (text) of articles

On average articles that have 50 sentences, 1000 words orabout 5000 characters tend to be real. Words such as election, president, hillary and government appear often in fake articles. While, words such as voters, democratic, political and law appear often in real articles. The dominating topic of articles in the dataset lean towards politics and election.

The dataset contain text issues which can be fixed with the following methods:

  1. Lowercase all the text
  2. Expand Contractions
  3. Remove punctuations
  4. Remove emojis
  5. Remove digits
